  {# ======================================================================= #}
  {# 1. WHAT IS CITGO?                                                       #}
  {# ======================================================================= #}
  <section id="what-is-citgo" class="sec">
    <h2>1. What Is Citgo?</h2>
    <p class="sec-lead">
      Citgo Petroleum Corporation is a US-based refiner, transporter, and marketer
      of petroleum products&mdash;and the most valuable overseas asset of the
      Venezuelan state.
    </p>

    <p>
      Citgo traces its origins to 1910, when Henry Doherty founded Cities Service
      Company in Bartlesville, Oklahoma. The company grew into a major integrated oil
      firm before being acquired by Occidental Petroleum in 1982. In 1983, the retail
      and refining operations were rebranded as &ldquo;Citgo,&rdquo; and the company
      was subsequently purchased by the Southland Corporation before Petr&oacute;leos
      de Venezuela (PDVSA) acquired a 50% stake in 1986 and full ownership in 1990
      for approximately $1.3&nbsp;billion.
    </p>
    <p>
      Today, Citgo is the 7th-largest US refiner by capacity and a fixture of the
      American fuel landscape. The company operates:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Three refineries</strong> with a combined capacity of approximately 769,000&nbsp;barrels per day (bpd): Lemont, Illinois (172,000&nbsp;bpd); Corpus Christi, Texas (165,000&nbsp;bpd); and Lake Charles, Louisiana (432,000&nbsp;bpd).</li>
      <li><strong>48 petroleum product terminals</strong> and <strong>4 ethanol production plants</strong> across the eastern and Gulf Coast states.</li>
      <li><strong>~4,600 independently owned and operated gas stations</strong> branded under the Citgo name in 30 states and the District of Columbia.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Despite being wholly owned by a Venezuelan state entity, Citgo operates as an
      American company, headquartered in Houston, Texas, employing approximately
      3,400 US workers, paying US taxes, and subject to US corporate law and regulation.
      This unique dual identity&mdash;Venezuelan-owned but American-operated&mdash;is
      at the heart of every legal and political battle surrounding the company.
    </p>
  </section>

  {# ======================================================================= #}
  {# 2. OWNERSHIP STRUCTURE                                                   #}
  {# ======================================================================= #}
  <section id="ownership" class="sec">
    <h2>2. Ownership Structure &amp; PDVSA Connection</h2>
    <p class="sec-lead">
      Citgo&rsquo;s corporate structure is a layered chain stretching from the
      Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela to a Delaware-incorporated petroleum company.
    </p>

    <div class="ownership-chain">
      <div class="chain-node">Government of Venezuela</div>
      <span class="chain-arrow">&rarr;</span>
      <div class="chain-node">PDVSA</div>
      <span class="chain-arrow">&rarr;</span>
      <div class="chain-node">PDV Holding, Inc.</div>
      <span class="chain-arrow">&rarr;</span>
      <div class="chain-node">Citgo Holding, Inc.</div>
      <span class="chain-arrow">&rarr;</span>
      <div class="chain-node">Citgo Petroleum Corp.</div>
    </div>

    <p>
      PDVSA acquired Citgo in two stages. In 1986, PDVSA&rsquo;s US subsidiary purchased
      a 50% interest in Citgo from the Southland Corporation (then parent of 7-Eleven).
      In 1990, PDVSA acquired the remaining 50% for approximately $1.3&nbsp;billion,
      gaining full control. The acquisition was part of PDVSA&rsquo;s
      &ldquo;internationalization&rdquo; strategy under its pre-Ch&aacute;vez technocratic
      management, which sought to secure downstream outlets for Venezuelan heavy crude
      in the world&rsquo;s largest refining market.
    </p>
    <p>
      For three decades, Citgo functioned as a commercially managed subsidiary, remitting
      dividends to PDVSA and processing Venezuelan crude in its Gulf Coast and Midwest
      refineries. By the time Hugo Ch&aacute;vez came to power in 1999, Citgo had
      become Venezuela&rsquo;s single most valuable overseas asset&mdash;a status it
      retains today.
    </p>

    <h3>Board control shift (2019)</h3>
    <p>
      In January 2019, the United States recognized National Assembly President Juan
      Guaid&oacute; as Venezuela&rsquo;s legitimate interim president. Under Guaid&oacute;&rsquo;s
      authority, a new board of directors was appointed for PDV Holding and Citgo Holding,
      replacing the Maduro-appointed directors. This board&mdash;composed of Venezuelan
      opposition-aligned figures&mdash;has controlled Citgo&rsquo;s corporate governance
      since February 2019 with US government backing.
    </p>
    <p>
      Following the January 2026 political transition in Venezuela, the Rodr&iacute;guez
      interim government has sought to restore its own board appointees to Citgo&rsquo;s
      parent companies. As of mid-{{ current_year }}, the board composition remains a
      contested legal and diplomatic question, with the Guaid&oacute;-era directors
      arguing their mandate continues until a democratically elected Venezuelan government
      is established.
    </p>
  </section>

  {# ======================================================================= #}
  {# 3. OWNERSHIP BATTLE TIMELINE                                             #}
  {# ======================================================================= #}
  <section id="ownership-battle" class="sec">
    <h2>3. The Citgo Ownership Battle</h2>
    <p class="sec-lead">
      Citgo is at the center of one of the most complex international asset disputes
      in modern corporate history, with over $21&nbsp;billion in competing creditor
      claims against its parent company&rsquo;s shares.
    </p>

    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="tl-item negative">
        <span class="tl-dot"></span>
        <div class="tl-date">2007</div>
        <div class="tl-title">Ch&aacute;vez threatens to sell Citgo</div>
        <div class="tl-desc">
          During a diplomatic confrontation with the Bush administration, President
          Hugo Ch&aacute;vez publicly threatens to sell or shut down Citgo. The threat
          is not carried out, but it marks the first time Citgo&rsquo;s future becomes
          a geopolitical bargaining chip.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl-item negative">
        <span class="tl-dot"></span>
        <div class="tl-date">October 2016</div>
        <div class="tl-title">PDVSA pledges 50.1% of Citgo shares to Rosneft</div>
        <div class="tl-desc">
          In a desperate bid for cash, PDVSA pledges 50.1% of the shares of Citgo
          Holding as collateral for a $1.5&nbsp;billion loan from Russian state oil
          company Rosneft. The deal sparks alarm in Washington over the prospect of
          a Russian entity gaining control of critical US refining infrastructure.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl-item negative">
        <span class="tl-dot"></span>
        <div class="tl-date">August 2017</div>
        <div class="tl-title">Trump sanctions block PDVSA dividend payments</div>
        <div class="tl-desc">
          Executive Order 13808 bans dealing in new PDVSA debt, effectively preventing
          Citgo from paying dividends upstream to its Venezuelan parent. This severs the
          financial pipeline that had funneled billions from Citgo to the Venezuelan
          government.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl-item positive">
        <span class="tl-dot"></span>
        <div class="tl-date">January 2019</div>
        <div class="tl-title">US recognizes Guaid&oacute;; new Citgo board appointed</div>
        <div class="tl-desc">
          Following US recognition of Juan Guaid&oacute;, a new opposition-aligned board
          takes control of PDV Holding and Citgo Holding. Concurrently, OFAC issues
          protective orders that effectively shield Citgo from creditor seizure,
          designating PDVSA as an SDN while carving out Citgo&rsquo;s operations
          through general licenses.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl-item negative">
        <span class="tl-dot"></span>
        <div class="tl-date">October 2020</div>
        <div class="tl-title">PDVSA 2020 bond default triggers creditor claims</div>
        <div class="tl-desc">
          PDVSA&rsquo;s 2020 bonds&mdash;which were backed by a pledge of 50.1% of
          PDV Holding shares&mdash;default after PDVSA fails to make the final
          $913&nbsp;million payment. Bondholders move to enforce their collateral
          rights against the Citgo shares. Rosneft had previously transferred its
          Citgo collateral to a Russian government entity, which subsequently sold
          the rights to unnamed buyers.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl-item negative">
        <span class="tl-dot"></span>
        <div class="tl-date">2023</div>
        <div class="tl-title">Delaware court orders auction of PDV Holding shares</div>
        <div class="tl-desc">
          Judge Leonard P. Stark of the US District Court for the District of Delaware
          orders that 100% of the shares of PDV Holding be sold to satisfy creditor
          claims. The court consolidates competing claims totaling approximately
          $21.3&nbsp;billion from multiple creditors including ConocoPhillips,
          Crystallex, Gold Reserve, and PDVSA 2020 bondholders.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl-item">
        <span class="tl-dot"></span>
        <div class="tl-date">2024</div>
        <div class="tl-title">Elliott Investment Management wins auction bid</div>
        <div class="tl-desc">
          Elliott Investment Management, the activist hedge fund led by Paul Singer,
          wins the court-supervised auction for PDV Holding with a bid of approximately
          $7.3&nbsp;billion. The bid would give Elliott control of Citgo&rsquo;s three
          refineries and all downstream assets. Treasury Department review is required
          before the sale can close.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl-item">
        <span class="tl-dot"></span>
        <div class="tl-date">2025</div>
        <div class="tl-title">Treasury review of Elliott acquisition begins</div>
        <div class="tl-desc">
          The Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States (CFIUS) and the
          Treasury Department begin formal review of the Elliott acquisition. The
          review considers national security implications of transferring
          Venezuelan-state-owned refining assets to a private equity firm.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl-item pending">
        <span class="tl-dot"></span>
        <div class="tl-date">January 2026</div>
        <div class="tl-title">Rodr&iacute;guez government contests sale</div>
        <div class="tl-desc">
          Following the January 2026 political transition in Venezuela, the
          Rodr&iacute;guez interim government formally contests the sale, arguing that
          the new government should be given the opportunity to satisfy creditor claims
          and retain ownership of Citgo. Treasury pauses the CFIUS review pending
          diplomatic engagement with the transitional government.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl-item pending">
        <span class="tl-dot"></span>
        <div class="tl-date">2026 (current)</div>
        <div class="tl-title">Ownership resolution pending</div>
        <div class="tl-desc">
          As of {{ updated_label }}, Citgo continues to operate under the OFAC
          protective framework. The Elliott sale remains under Treasury review. The
          Rodr&iacute;guez government is negotiating with major creditors on a
          potential settlement framework that would preserve Venezuelan state ownership.
          No resolution timeline has been confirmed.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ======================================================================= #}
  {# 4. CITGO REFINERIES                                                      #}
  {# ======================================================================= #}
  <section id="refineries" class="sec">
    <h2>4. Citgo Refineries</h2>
    <p class="sec-lead">
      Citgo operates three major US refineries with a combined throughput capacity of
      approximately 769,000&nbsp;barrels per day, making it one of the largest refining
      systems in the United States.
    </p>

    <div class="card-grid cols-3">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Largest facility</div>
        <h3>Lake Charles, Louisiana</h3>
        <div class="row"><strong>Capacity</strong>432,000 bpd</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Nelson Index</strong>11.5</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Crude slate</strong>Heavy &amp; medium sour</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Products</strong>Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, petrochemicals</div>
        <div class="note">
          Citgo&rsquo;s flagship facility and one of the largest refineries in the US.
          Historically configured to process Venezuelan heavy crude from the Orinoco Belt.
          Includes coking, hydrocracking, and catalytic cracking units enabling processing
          of the heaviest crude grades.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Highest complexity</div>
        <h3>Corpus Christi, Texas</h3>
        <div class="row"><strong>Capacity</strong>165,000 bpd</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Nelson Index</strong>12.8</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Crude slate</strong>Light to heavy</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Products</strong>Gasoline, diesel, asphalt, aromatics</div>
        <div class="note">
          Located on the Texas Gulf Coast with deepwater access for crude imports and
          product exports. The highest-complexity Citgo refinery, capable of processing
          a wide range of crude grades. Significant asphalt and aromatics production
          alongside transportation fuels.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Midwest supply</div>
        <h3>Lemont, Illinois</h3>
        <div class="row"><strong>Capacity</strong>172,000 bpd</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Nelson Index</strong>11.0</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Crude slate</strong>Light sweet &amp; Canadian heavy</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Products</strong>Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel</div>
        <div class="note">
          Serves the greater Chicago metropolitan area and Midwest markets. Connected
          to Canadian crude supply via pipeline infrastructure. Strategically positioned
          as one of the few major refineries in the PADD II (Midwest) region.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      Combined, the three refineries give Citgo a total nameplate capacity of
      769,000&nbsp;bpd. The system&rsquo;s high Nelson Complexity Index
      (averaging ~11.5 across all three plants) reflects significant upgrading
      capability&mdash;the ability to convert lower-value heavy crude into
      higher-value light products like gasoline and diesel. This complexity was
      deliberately engineered by PDVSA to create a captive downstream market for
      Venezuela&rsquo;s heavy Orinoco crude.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since US sanctions severed Citgo&rsquo;s supply of Venezuelan crude in 2019,
      the refineries have shifted to processing alternative heavy feedstocks,
      including Canadian oil sands crude, Colombian heavy grades, and domestically
      produced sour crudes.
    </p>
  </section>

  {# ======================================================================= #}
  {# 5. OFAC SANCTIONS & CITGO                                                #}
  {# ======================================================================= #}
  <section id="sanctions" class="sec">
    <h2>5. OFAC Sanctions &amp; Citgo</h2>
    <p class="sec-lead">
      Citgo exists in a unique regulatory limbo&mdash;owned by a sanctioned entity
      (PDVSA) but authorized to operate through a carefully constructed framework
      of OFAC general licenses.
    </p>

    <h3>Key executive orders affecting Citgo</h3>
    <table class="em-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Executive Order</th>
          <th>Date</th>
          <th>Impact on Citgo</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>E.O. 13808</td>
          <td>Aug 2017</td>
          <td>Blocked new PDVSA debt transactions; prevented Citgo from issuing debt to benefit PDVSA</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>E.O. 13850</td>
          <td>Nov 2018</td>
          <td>Authorized sanctions on any sector of Venezuelan economy; gold sector designated</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="highlight">
          <td>PDVSA SDN designation</td>
          <td>Jan 2019</td>
          <td>PDVSA added to SDN list; Citgo operations preserved through general licenses</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>E.O. 13884</td>
          <td>Aug 2019</td>
          <td>Full embargo on Government of Venezuela; strengthened blocking of PDVSA/Citgo dividend flows</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>E.O. 13857</td>
          <td>Jan 2019</td>
          <td>Recognized Guaid&oacute; government; enabled transfer of Citgo corporate governance to opposition board</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>How Citgo continues to operate</h3>
    <p>
      Citgo&rsquo;s ability to function as a normal US business despite its sanctioned
      parentage rests on OFAC General License 3 (as amended, currently GL&nbsp;3K).
      This license authorizes all transactions ordinarily incident to the day-to-day
      operations of Citgo Petroleum Corporation, including:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Purchasing crude oil and other feedstocks on the open market</li>
      <li>Selling refined products (gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, petrochemicals)</li>
      <li>Maintaining banking and credit relationships with US financial institutions</li>
      <li>Paying employees, contractors, and suppliers</li>
      <li>Operating its retail brand licensing program</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>What Citgo cannot do</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Dividend repatriation:</strong> Citgo cannot remit profits, dividends, or any other funds upstream to PDVSA or the Government of Venezuela without specific OFAC authorization.</li>
      <li><strong>Venezuelan crude processing:</strong> Prior to GL&nbsp;50A (Feb 2026), Citgo could not purchase or process Venezuelan-origin crude. The current status of Citgo&rsquo;s ability to resume Venezuelan crude imports is subject to the ongoing ownership proceedings.</li>
      <li><strong>Related-party transactions:</strong> Any transaction that would benefit PDVSA or other blocked persons requires specific OFAC authorization beyond the general license.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Creditor protection framework</h3>
    <p>
      A critical but often overlooked function of the sanctions framework is creditor
      protection. Executive orders and OFAC directives have effectively prevented
      creditors from seizing Citgo assets or forcing a sale without US government
      approval. This protection has preserved Citgo as a going concern through years
      of litigation, ensuring that approximately 3,400 American jobs and a significant
      share of US refining capacity are not disrupted by the legal battle over
      PDVSA&rsquo;s debts.
    </p>

    <h3>Current 2026 licensing status</h3>
    <p>
      As of {{ updated_label }}, Citgo continues to operate under GL&nbsp;3K. The
      January 2026 political transition has not yet resulted in changes to Citgo&rsquo;s
      specific licensing framework, though broader Venezuela general licenses (GL&nbsp;50A
      and GL&nbsp;52) have opened the oil sector to new activity. Any resolution of the
      ownership dispute will require OFAC concurrence to ensure compliance with the
      sanctions framework.
    </p>
  </section>

